Q4. Gate drive design for half-bridge:
High-side MOSFET S1: Q_g=20nC, V_gate=12V. Gate driver: IR2110 (peak output 2A). Bootstrap capacitor.
(a) Minimum bootstrap capacitor: C_boot ≥ Q_g/ΔV where ΔV=0.5V
(b) Bootstrap capacitor charges through bootstrap diode when S2 is ON. If S2 minimum ON time = 2µs and bootstrap charging resistance R_boot=10Ω: find τ_boot=R_boot×C_boot. Is there enough time to charge C_boot to within 5% (5τ) before S1 turns on?
(c) At D=0.48 (near maximum): S2 ON time = (0.5−0.48)×T = 0.02×10µs = 0.2µs. Is there sufficient time to recharge C_boot? What happens to high-side drive at extreme duty cycles?
(d) The IR2110 has under-voltage lockout (UVLO) at V_bootstrap < 8.6V. If C_boot=100nF loses charge through MOSFET gate leakage (I_leak=1µA) over the maximum S1 ON time: calculate voltage droop. Is UVLO a concern?
(e) Why does the half-bridge topology REQUIRE a bootstrap or isolated gate drive for the high-side MOSFET, while the low-side MOSFET can be driven directly from a ground-referenced signal?
Q5. Complete loss budget: V_DC=380V, V_out=12V, I_load=10A, f_s=100kHz, D=0.40, n=3/38.
MOSFET: R_DS_on=0.8Ω at 150°C, Q_gd=8nC, I_gate=1.5A, Q_g=20nC, V_gate=12V.
Secondary Schottky: V_f=0.5V. L_out=3.3µH, R_L=5mΩ.
(a) Primary RMS current: I_p_rms = I_load × n × √(2D)
(b) MOSFET conduction loss (both MOSFETs): P_cond = 2 × I_p_rms² × R_DS_on
(c) MOSFET switching loss: t_sw = Q_gd/I_gate, P_sw = 2 × (V_DC/2) × I_p_peak × t_sw × f_s (each MOSFET switches against V_DC/2)
(d) Secondary diode conduction loss: P_D = V_f × I_load
(e) Total loss, output power, efficiency. Is this topology achieving better efficiency than the flyback at this power level?
